  - key: '[주-D001] 노(盧)나라에 이르기 : '
    value: 《논어》에 “제나라가 한 번 변하면 노나라에 이른다.[齊一變至於魯].” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 태평(太平) 직금(織錦)의 작(作) : '
    value: 진성여왕(眞聖女王)이 당나라 황제에게 바친 송시(頌詩).
  - key: '[주-D003] 왕릉(王陵) : '
    value: 한나라 고조(高祖)의 공신(功臣). 혜제(惠帝) 때 여후(呂后)가 모든 여씨(呂氏)를 왕으로 삼으려 하여, 왕이 우승상(右丞相)인 능(陵)에게 물으니, “불가하다.” 하므로, 태부(太傅)로 옮겼다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 드높은 저 남산 : '
    value: 《시경》 절남산(節南山)에 나오는 구절로, 제 구실을 못하는 사윤(師尹)를 풍자한 시.
  - key: '[주-D005] 구족(九族)을 친함 : '
    value: 《서경》 요전(堯典)에 “능히 큰 덕을 밝혀야 구족이 친하고, 구족이 화목하여야 백성을 평정한다[克明俊德以親九族 九族旣睦 平章百姓].” 하였다.
english:
  title: Memorial of Gratitude
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant humbly reports:

    Your servant's uncle Tan has taken office as regent of our tributary state. On the seventh day of the seventh month in the fourth year of Qianning, when the imperial envoy Choe Won, who had come to court as superintendent of congratulations and bearer of the purple pouch, returned to our land, your servant received a royal decree awarding posthumous honors: to our late grandfather, the Grand Administrator and Generalissimo of Gyerim, investing him as Grand Preceptor; and to our late father, the Minister of Military Affairs, investing him as Grand Mentor. Each received an official patent. Thus has the imperial grace descended from the celestial household, and its radiance illuminates our dwelling. All the lands of the Eastern sea are stirred with gratitude; even in the netherworld, our forebears may hear and understand that joy is but sorrow's twin, and that glory itself is the seed of fear.

    Your servant humbly considers that our kingdom has always revered the righteousness of earth, as the nation looks to heaven's compassion. Thus did our remote ancestor, King Sinmun, seek the wisdom of the Rites, and the Sage Emperor Xuanzong especially granted us the Classic of Filial Piety, so that the transformation of our people became luminous in the official records. Your servant respectfully notes what the Rites teach: "If descendants who guard the ancestral temples do not know of their ancestors' virtues, they lack clarity; if they know yet fail to transmit them, they lack benevolence." And the Classic states: "To establish oneself and bring honor to one's name, thereby displaying one's parents—this is the perfection of filial duty."

    Our late grandfather, the Grand Preceptor, lived in the era of Xiantong when the imperial civilization spread widely and the whole world moved in harmony. The sage virtue reached even to the eastern lands where the sun rises. Though his body remained bound to these distant realms and his heart yearned toward the far north, unable to witness the glories of Zhou, he devoted himself to the Confucian way, hoping only to reach the state of Lu. Though occupied with official duties, he found joy in learning. He composed verses honoring the edicts of Central Harmony and admired the commemorative poems of Great Peace written by those before him. In time, he authored the "Treatise on Seeking the Worthy" and composed six stanzas praising the imperial transformation, thereby celebrating both the virtue of harmonizing and attracting distant peoples, and the talents of the eminent and lofty. These works were shown to our people and remain treasured by our house. Though his form has passed away, surely his name remains undimmed and worthy to be beheld.

    As for our late father, the Grand Mentor, in the later years of Qianfu when turmoil arose upon the seas and disturbances spread through the passes, bandits pressed hard upon the central provinces and the court moved westward to Shu. Our ancestor rose to answer the call, determined to serve unto death in the imperial cause. Yet the military commissioner of Huainan, desiring only to observe from afar rather than commit fully, merely reported our state's readiness while displaying his own strength. Meanwhile, the regional commander of Qingzhou, fearing overstepping his bounds, blocked our path to service through his messenger, saying he wished to safeguard the rear—yet his true intent seemed to forget the front. Thus our ancestor's loyal passion could not be fulfilled, and his regret became lasting.

    So it was that our grandfather revered the ways of culture, and our father wished to aid in military achievement. Throughout our nation's history from the age of Martial Virtue to that of Kaiyuan, whenever national mourning occurred, the upper kingdoms granted posthumous honors. Yet these honors came to be curtailed, bringing shame to our distant land. Our late father left sorrowful wishes that his son Tan would pursue filial devotion. The uncle, grieving as the flowers of brotherhood fade, grew ever more devoted to honoring the departed, yearning to the clouded heaven above, hoping his forebears would receive recognition upon the hills. Though this boundless longing may be forgiven, such insatiable desire could hardly escape reproach.

    Yet now, unexpectedly, the emperor has shown sagely compassion, graciously granting our humble petition. The lofty titles of noble rank have been extended to the spiritual essence of those dwelling in foreign realms. Thus is the great filial duty of honoring parents blessed, and this humble servant, receiving such grace, can never repay even in ten thousand deaths.

    The title of Grand Preceptor was bestowed by the Zhou rulers upon Bigan of Yin in ancient times, and in recent years by the Tang emperor Dezong upon Guo Ziyi. The title of Grand Mentor was held by Wang Ling, who commanded universal respect through his noble character, and by Hu Guang, whose virtue of moderation first brought him rightful appointment. Though we cannot compare those of past ages with those living now, nor equate the distant with the near, the imperial favor has been extended even to the netherworld, and the celestial wave has reached our shores. Neither through merit nor accomplishment have our grandfather and father received such honors—only through the mysterious ways of heaven.

    Though we, here in this distant place, are ashamed when measured against the three great ministers, and though cast upon the eastern sea, we cherish only the precedence of the hundred virtues. May the commendations of the great kingdoms become the glory of our state, and may the transmission of the filial son's deeds bring some small honor to our house. Uncle Tan humbly ventures to hope for the love of all kinfolk, while your servant reveres the noble examples before us.

    Your servant dwells in these four counties in lowly station, mourning the departed in the nine springs below. Unable to hasten to the celestial court to weep gratitude at the clouded steps of the throne...
  footnotes:
    - 'The reference to reaching the state of Lu alludes to the Analects: "If Qi were to reform, it would reach the state of Lu." This expresses the ideal of gradual moral transformation through sage influence.'
    - The "Great Peace Tapestry" refers to commemorative verses presented by Queen Jinseong to the Tang emperor.
    - Wang Ling was a Han dynasty general under Emperor Gao who earned the title of Grand Mentor through his steadfast character and principled opposition to improper rule.
    - The allusion to lofty Mount Nan comes from the Book of Poetry and refers to ministers who fail in their duties.
    - The "nine kinfolk" comes from the Classic of Documents, referring to the proper ordering of nine degrees of kinship as the foundation for governing all people.
